04506nam a22007095i 9780231509831DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008020179  a(OCoLC)979904194  a97802315098317 a10.7312/mill136122doi  a(DE-B1597)459137  a(OCoLC)817924463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDP103b.M55 2008 4aDP103 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a305.6/970946553090241 aMiller, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGuardians of Islam :bReligious Authority and Muslim Communities of Late Medieval Spain /cKathryn Miller. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. The Muslim Exclaves in Christian Spain -- tChapter one. On the Border of Infidelity -- tChapter two. From Dar al-Islam to Dar al-Harb: Landscapes of Mudejar Spain -- tChapter three. Transmitting Knowledge and Building Networks -- tChapter four. Write It Down! -- tChapter five. Pretending to Be Jurists -- tChapter six. The Scholar’s Jihad, the Mudejar Mosque, and Preaching -- tChapter seven. Captive Redemption: From Dar al-Harb to Dar al-Islam -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuslim enclaves within non-Islamic polities are commonly believed to have been beleaguered communities undergoing relentless cultural and religious decline. Cut off from the Islamic world, these Muslim groups, it is assumed, passively yielded to political, social, and economic forces of assimilation and acculturation before finally accepting Christian dogma. Kathryn A. Miller radically reconceptualizes what she calls the exclave experience of medieval Muslim minorities. By focusing on the legal scholars (faqihs) of fifteenth-century Aragonese Muslim communities and translating little-known and newly discovered texts, she unearths a sustained effort to connect with Muslim coreligionaries and preserve practice and belief in the face of Christian influences. Devoted to securing and disseminating Islamic knowledge, these local authorities intervened in Christian courts on behalf of Muslims, provided Arabic translations, and taught and advised other Muslims. Miller follows the activities of the faqihs, their dialogue with Islamic authorities in nearby Muslim polities, their engagement with Islamic texts, and their pursuit of traditional ideals of faith. She demonstrates that these local scholars played a critical role as cultural mediators, creating scholarly networks and communal solidarity despite living in an environment dominated by Christianity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMudéjareszSpainxHistory. 0aMudéjareszSpainxHistory. 0aMuslimszSpainxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mill1361240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231509831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231509831/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK